INSERT INTO `summarize_notes` VALUES (13,'2026-03-23 22:43:52.672706','rosedawson@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for a text summarizer application. It uses the `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the user clicks the \"Summarize Text\" button, the `handleSummarize` function is triggered, which sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization. If the input is empty, it prompts the user to provide text. The API response is then displayed in a styled output box. The component includes a textarea for input, a button to initiate summarization, and a section to display the generated summary. The UI is styled with a gradient background, a custom card design, and responsive elements.','m'),(15,'2026-03-23 22:45:44.367901','rose@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for an AI Text Summarizer page. It uses the `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the user clicks the \"Summarize Text\" button, it sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization. If the input is empty, it displays a warning. During the API call, a loading state is shown. The summary or error message is then displayed in a styled output box. The page features a gradient background, a centered card with a textarea for input, a custom button, and responsive styling for a user-friendly interface.','m'),(30,'2026-03-23 22:58:42.610172','rose@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for an AI Text Summarizer page. It uses the `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the user clicks the \"Summarize Text\" button, it sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization. If the input is empty, it prompts the user to provide text. The API response is displayed as a summary, or an error message if the request fails. The component is styled with a gradient background, a custom card design, and responsive elements, ensuring a user-friendly interface for text summarization.','m'),(34,'2026-03-23 23:08:47.699904','rose@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for a text summarizer application. It uses the `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the user clicks the \"Summarize Text\" button, the `handleSummarize` function sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization. If the input is empty, it prompts the user to provide text. The API response is displayed as a summary, or an error message if the request fails. The component is styled with a gradient background, a custom card design, and responsive elements, ensuring a user-friendly interface for text summarization.','aef'),(43,'2026-03-23 23:18:44.904394','rose@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for an AI Text Summarizer page. It uses the `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the \"Summarize Text\" button is clicked, it sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization, handling errors and displaying the result. The UI includes a styled card with a textarea for input, a button to trigger summarization, and an output box to display the summary. The page has a gradient background and modern styling for a visually appealing user experience.','aef'),(46,'2026-03-23 23:21:04.156924','rose@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for an AI Text Summarizer page. It uses the `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the user clicks the \"Summarize Text\" button, it sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization. If the input is empty, it displays a warning. During the API call, a loading state is shown. The summary or error message is then displayed in a styled output box. The page features a gradient background, a custom card design, and responsive styling for a user-friendly interface.','aef'),(47,'2026-03-23 23:21:42.363465','rose@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for an AI Text Summarizer page. It uses React\'s `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the user clicks the \"Summarize Text\" button, it sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization. If the input is empty, it prompts the user to provide text. The API response is displayed as a summary, or an error message if the request fails. The page features a gradient background, a styled card for the summarizer, and a textarea for input. The summary is shown in a styled output box below the button.','aef'),(48,'2026-03-23 23:21:52.709935','rose@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for an AI Text Summarizer page. It uses the `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the user clicks the \"Summarize Text\" button, it sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization. If the input is empty, it prompts the user to provide text. The API response is displayed as a summary, or an error message if the request fails. The component is styled with a gradient background, a custom card design, and a responsive layout, featuring a textarea for input, a button to trigger summarization, and an output box to display the summary.','aef'),(49,'2026-03-23 23:25:14.483552','rosedawson@gmail.com','The text is a summary of the book \"Atomic Habits\" by James Clear, which focuses on the power of small habits and how they can lead to significant changes in one\'s life. The book is divided into several chapters, each exploring different aspects of habit formation and behavior change.\n\n**Key Points:**\n\n1. **Habits as Compound Interest:** The author compares habits to compound interest, emphasizing that small improvements in daily habits can lead to remarkable results over time. This concept is illustrated through the story of British Cycling\'s transformation from mediocrity to dominance in the sport.\n\n2. **Identity and Habits:** Clear discusses the relationship between identity and habits, suggesting that true behavior change occurs when habits become part of one\'s identity. He introduces the concept of \"identity-based habits,\" where individuals focus on becoming the type of person they want to be rather than just achieving specific outcomes.\n\n3. **Four Laws of Behavior Change:** The book introduces a four-step model for habit formation: cue, craving, response, and reward. Clear then presents the \"Four Laws of Behavior Change,\" which are practical strategies for creating good habits and breaking bad ones:\n   - **Make it Obvious:** Focus on awareness and clarity to make desired habits more noticeable.\n   - **Make it Attractive:** Increase the appeal of good habits by associating them with positive experiences.\n   - **Make it Easy:** Reduce friction and simplify the process of performing good habits.\n   - **Make it Satisfying:** Ensure that habits provide immediate satisfaction to reinforce their repetition.\n\n4. **Environment and Context:** The text highlights the importance of environment in shaping habits. Clear suggests that individuals can design their surroundings to make good habits more obvious and easier to perform while increasing friction for bad habits.\n\n5. **Reflection and Review:** The author emphasizes the need for periodic reflection and review to ensure that habits remain effective and aligned with one\'s goals. This process involves assessing progress, making adjustments, and breaking free from limiting beliefs.\n\n6. **Mastery and Deliberate Practice:** Clear discusses the difference between automatic habits and deliberate practice, suggesting that a combination of both is necessary for mastery. He introduces the concept of the \"Goldilocks Rule,\" where individuals experience peak motivation when working on tasks that are right on the edge of their current abilities.\n\n**Overall, \"Atomic Habits\" provides a comprehensive guide to understanding and changing habits, emphasizing the power of small, consistent improvements and the importance of aligning habits with one\'s identity and environment.**','atomic habits'),(50,'2026-03-23 23:25:35.625484','rose@gmail.com','The `AdminDashBoard` component is a React functional component that fetches and displays an admin\'s profile information. It uses `useState` and `useEffect` hooks to manage state and side effects. The admin\'s email is retrieved from `localStorage`, and an API request is made to fetch the admin\'s data, including their name, phone number, and profile picture. The profile picture can be updated via navigation state or fetched from the database. The component renders an `AdminHeader`, a profile picture, and the admin\'s details (name, email, and phone number) in a styled layout. If there\'s an error fetching data, it logs the error to the console.','hcef'),(51,'2026-03-24 14:34:06.001758','rose@gmail.com','The `AdminDashBoard` component is a React functional component that fetches and displays an admin\'s profile information, including their name, email, phone number, and profile picture. It uses `useState` and `useEffect` hooks to manage state and side effects. The admin\'s email is retrieved from `localStorage`, and an API request is made to fetch the admin\'s data from a backend server. The profile picture is dynamically set based on whether an image URL is passed from navigation, an image exists in the database, or a default image is used. The component renders an `AdminHeader` and a section displaying the admin\'s details, including their profile picture and contact information.','harry'),(52,'2026-03-24 14:37:52.101655','rose@gmail.com','The `AdminDashBoard` component is a React functional component that fetches and displays an admin\'s profile information. It uses `useState` and `useEffect` hooks to manage state and side effects. The admin\'s email is retrieved from `localStorage`, and an API request is made to fetch their profile data, including name, phone number, and profile picture. The profile picture is dynamically set based on whether it\'s provided from navigation state, stored in the database, or defaults to a placeholder image. The component renders an `AdminHeader`, a circular profile image, and the admin\'s details (name, email, and phone) in a styled layout. The `useEffect` hook ensures data fetching occurs once on component mount.','harry'),(53,'2026-03-24 14:41:18.860160','rose@gmail.com','The `AdminDashBoard` component is a React functional component that fetches and displays an admin\'s profile information. It uses `useState` and `useEffect` hooks to manage state and side effects. The admin\'s email is retrieved from `localStorage`, and an API call is made to fetch the admin\'s data, including their name, phone number, and profile picture. The profile picture is dynamically set based on whether it\'s provided from navigation state, stored in the database, or a default image. The component renders an `AdminHeader`, a profile picture, and the admin\'s details (name, email, and phone) in a styled layout. The `useEffect` hook ensures data fetching occurs only once on component mount.','harry'),(54,'2026-03-24 14:42:14.632085','rose@gmail.com','The `AdminDashBoard` component is a React functional component that fetches and displays an admin\'s profile information. It uses `useState` and `useEffect` hooks to manage state and side effects. The admin\'s email is retrieved from `localStorage`, and an API request is made to fetch the admin\'s data, including their name, phone number, and profile picture. The profile picture is dynamically set based on whether an image URL is passed from navigation or if an image exists in the database. If neither is available, a default profile picture is used. The component renders an `AdminHeader`, a profile image, and the admin\'s details (name, email, and phone number) in a styled layout. The `useLocation` hook is used to access any state passed during navigation, such as an updated profile image URL.','harry'),(55,'2026-03-24 14:51:13.547674','rose@gmail.com','The provided code is a React component for an AI Text Summarizer page. It uses the `useState` hook to manage input text, summary, and loading states. When the user clicks the \"Summarize Text\" button, it sends the input text to the Cohere API for summarization. If the input is empty, it displays a warning. During the API call, a loading state is shown. The summary or error message is then displayed in a styled output box. The page features a gradient background, a centered card with a textarea for input, a button to trigger summarization, and a section to display the summary. The styling includes custom gradients, shadows, and responsive design for a visually appealing user interface.','abcd'),(56,'2026-03-24 16:50:31.118900','rose@gmail.com','This text outlines the creation of two React components within an existing React application named `useEffectApp`. The first component, `Notice.jsx`, fetches notification data from a mock API using Axios and `useEffect`, stores it with `useState`, and displays it in card format using Flexbox. The second component, `Product.jsx`, fetches product data from another API, stores it with `useState`, and displays it in a table format with columns for title, price, category, description, and image. Both components are styled with basic CSS and rendered within `App.js`.','ad'),(57,'2026-03-24 19:41:22.665933','roseda@gmail.com','The text provides an in-depth overview of various display technologies and computer graphics concepts, focusing on Cathode Ray Tube (CRT), Raster Scan, and Random-Scan displays, as well as the viewing pipeline and clipping algorithms in computer graphics. CRTs, once widely used in televisions and monitors, operate by directing an electron beam onto a phosphorescent screen to create images, offering high refresh rates and vibrant colors but being bulky and power-intensive. Raster Scan displays, common in modern screens, refresh the entire screen line by line, supporting complex images and color gradients but requiring significant memory. Random-Scan displays, or vector displays, draw images by tracing lines directly, excelling in high-resolution line art but limited to simple graphics. The viewing pipeline transforms 3D scenes into 2D screen representations using world and viewport coordinates, while clipping algorithms like Cohen-Sutherland and Sutherland-Hodgman determine visible portions of objects within a defined window, optimizing rendering efficiency. These technologies and techniques form the foundation of modern computer graphics and display systems.','rose dawson notes'),(58,'2026-03-24 19:54:51.293329','roseda@gmail.com','The text provides an in-depth overview of various display technologies and computer graphics concepts. It begins by explaining **Cathode Ray Tube (CRT)** technology, detailing its working principle, components, advantages (high refresh rates, deep blacks, vibrant colors), and disadvantages (bulkiness, high power consumption, electromagnetic radiation). CRTs were widely used in older televisions and computer monitors before being replaced by LCD and LED displays. The text also covers **Raster Scan Displays**, which are common in modern monitors and TVs, operating by scanning an electron beam across the screen in a systematic pattern to create images. These displays are pixel-based, use a frame buffer, and support complex images with shading and color control. However, they require high memory and can suffer from flickering at low refresh rates.\n\nNext, **Random-Scan Displays** (vector displays) are discussed, which draw images by tracing lines directly on the screen, making them ideal for technical drawings and line art. They offer high resolution and smooth lines but are limited to line-based graphics and are less efficient for complex images. The text then compares raster and random-scan displays, highlighting their differences in working principles, refresh processes, memory requirements, and applications.\n\nThe latter part of the text delves into **computer graphics fundamentals**, including the **viewing pipeline**, which transforms 3D scenes into 2D screen representations. It explains concepts like **world coordinates**, **windows**, **viewports**, and **normalization**. Additionally, it covers **clipping**, a process used to determine visible portions of an image, with algorithms like **Cohen-Sutherland Line Clipping** explained in detail. Clipping is essential for optimizing rendering and handling large or partially visible objects.\n\nIn summary, the text comprehensively explores display technologies (CRT, raster scan, random scan) and computer graphics principles (viewing pipeline, clipping), providing both theoretical foundations and practical applications.','rose dawson notes'),(59,'2026-03-24 20:00:46.087952','roseda@gmail.com','The text provides an in-depth overview of display technologies, focusing on **Cathode Ray Tube (CRT)**, **Raster Scan Displays**, and **Random-Scan Displays**, along with the **viewing pipeline** and **clipping algorithms** in computer graphics. CRTs, once widely used in TVs and monitors, operate by directing an electron beam onto a phosphorescent screen to create images. They are now largely replaced by LCD and LED displays due to their bulkiness and high power consumption. Raster scan displays, common in modern screens, refresh the entire screen line by line, using a pixel-based grid for image representation. Random-scan displays, or vector displays, draw images by tracing lines directly, offering high resolution for line art but limited to simple graphics. The viewing pipeline transforms 3D scenes into 2D screen representations using world, viewport, and device coordinates. Clipping algorithms, such as **Cohen-Sutherland** and **Sutherland-Hodgman**, determine visible portions of images or polygons within a defined window, optimizing rendering efficiency. These technologies and techniques form the foundation of modern computer graphics and display systems.','rose dawson notes'),(60,'2026-03-30 20:21:19.023696','rose@gmail.com','Selecting a cloud service provider (CSP) is a critical decision for businesses, involving a comprehensive evaluation of multiple factors to ensure the chosen solution meets operational, security, and financial requirements. The process begins with **software evaluation**, where compatibility, security, performance, and customization are assessed to ensure the cloud software aligns with the organization’s needs. This is followed by **system testing**, including load, performance, security, and disaster recovery tests, to validate the cloud infrastructure’s reliability and resilience. **Cost-cutting strategies** are then implemented to optimize cloud spending through methods like pay-as-you-go models, auto-scaling, and right-sizing resources. A **cost-benefit analysis** is conducted to compare costs (infrastructure, maintenance, migration) with benefits (efficiency, scalability, business continuity) and evaluate multiple providers. Finally, selecting a **scalable application** ensures the cloud solution can handle varying workloads, with options for vertical and horizontal scaling. Additional considerations include delivery model flexibility, trial usage, integration capabilities, security measures, platform compatibility, backups, upgrades, service level agreements, training, vendor viability, and adherence to standards for interoperability, portability, integration, and security. This structured approach ensures a well-informed decision, balancing technical, financial, and strategic needs.','abcd'),(61,'2026-04-05 20:45:21.550611','rose@gmail.com','Selecting a cloud service provider (CSP) is a critical decision for businesses, involving a comprehensive evaluation of multiple factors to ensure the chosen solution meets operational, security, and financial requirements. The process begins with **software evaluation**, assessing compatibility, security, performance, and customization options. Compatibility ensures seamless integration with existing IT infrastructure, while security involves evaluating data encryption, access control, and compliance with standards like GDPR, HIPAA, and ISO 27001. Performance and reliability are gauged through uptime, response time, and scalability. Customization and flexibility are essential for tailoring the software to specific business needs. \n\nNext, **system testing** is conducted to validate the cloud infrastructure\'s performance under various conditions. This includes load testing to assess handling of increasing workloads, performance testing to measure response times, security testing to identify vulnerabilities, and disaster recovery testing to ensure data redundancy and recovery processes. \n\n**Cost-cutting strategies** are crucial for optimizing cloud spending. Businesses can leverage pay-as-you-go models, auto-scaling to dynamically allocate resources, right-sizing resources to avoid over-provisioning, and utilizing reserved instances or savings plans for long-term commitments. Monitoring tools like AWS Cost Explorer or Azure Cost Management help track and optimize expenses.\n\nA **cost-benefit analysis (CBA)** is performed to justify the investment, comparing costs (infrastructure, maintenance, migration) with benefits (efficiency, scalability, reduced IT overhead). Multiple providers are compared based on pricing, uptime, and support to make an informed decision.\n\nFinally, selecting a **scalable application** ensures the cloud solution can handle varying workloads. Vertical scalability enhances a single machine\'s power, while horizontal scalability adds more machines for high availability. Best practices include ensuring auto-scaling and load balancing support, using containerization (Docker, Kubernetes), and adopting microservices architecture for flexibility.\n\nAdditional considerations include delivery model flexibility (public, private, or hybrid cloud), trial use of applications, integration capabilities, security measures, platform compatibility, backups, upgrades, service level agreements (SLAs), training, scalability, reference checks, and vendor viability. Adhering to standards and best practices ensures interoperability, portability, integration, and security, addressing challenges like proprietary APIs, data format incompatibility, and compliance issues. Ultimately, a well-structured selection process ensures businesses adopt a cloud solution that aligns with their long-term goals and operational needs.','abcd'),(62,'2026-04-05 20:45:51.909946','rose@gmail.com','Selecting a cloud service provider (CSP) is a critical decision for businesses, involving a comprehensive evaluation of multiple factors to ensure the chosen solution meets operational, security, and financial requirements. The process begins with **software evaluation**, assessing compatibility, security, performance, and customization options. This includes ensuring seamless integration with existing IT infrastructure, compliance with industry standards like GDPR and HIPAA, and high availability. **System testing** follows, encompassing load, performance, security, and disaster recovery tests to validate the cloud infrastructure\'s reliability under various conditions. **Cost-cutting strategies** are essential to optimize cloud spending, leveraging options like pay-as-you-go models, auto-scaling, and reserved instances. A **cost-benefit analysis** helps justify the investment by comparing costs (infrastructure, maintenance, migration) with benefits (scalability, efficiency, business continuity). Finally, selecting a **scalable application** ensures the solution can handle growing workloads, with options for vertical and horizontal scaling. Additional considerations include delivery model flexibility, trial usage, integration capabilities, security measures, and vendor viability. Adhering to standards and best practices, such as interoperability, portability, and security, is crucial for seamless cloud adoption. This structured approach ensures businesses make informed decisions, balancing technical, financial, and strategic needs in their cloud provider selection.','abcd'),(63,'2026-04-05 20:49:50.756665','rose@gmail.com','The assignment involves creating a React application named `third_app` with a structured folder organization, including `components` and `css` directories. The application will feature four main components: `Header.jsx` (a Bootstrap Navbar with navigation links), `Accordion.jsx` (a Bootstrap Accordion with Q&A content), `RegistrationForm.jsx` (a styled registration form using Bootstrap Input Groups, Font Awesome icons, and CSS Flexbox for a two-column layout), and `Footer.jsx` (a full-width Bootstrap footer). Custom CSS in `registration_form.css` will style the registration form, adjusting background colors, dimensions, borders, and box shadows. All components will be imported and rendered in `App.jsx` in the specified order: Header, Accordion, RegistrationForm, and Footer.','pdf'),(64,'2026-04-05 20:53:33.409755','rose@gmail.com','The assignment involves creating a React application named `third_app` with a structured folder organization, including `components` and `css` directories. The application requires four main components: `Header.jsx` (a Bootstrap Navbar with navigation links), `Accordion.jsx` (a Bootstrap Accordion with Q&A content), `RegistrationForm.jsx` (a styled registration form using Bootstrap Input Groups, Font Awesome icons, and CSS Flexbox for a two-column layout), and `Footer.jsx` (a full-width Bootstrap footer). Custom CSS in `registration_form.css` styles the registration form, adjusting background colors, dimensions, borders, and box shadows. All components are imported and rendered in `App.jsx` in the order: Header, Accordion, RegistrationForm, and Footer. The project emphasizes the integration of React, Bootstrap, and custom CSS for a functional and visually appealing UI.','re'),(65,'2026-04-05 21:08:00.361888','rose@gmail.com','The assignmen